{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.29,0.1,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4999"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28157"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17709"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a three-month history of ankle swelling and swelling around her eyes. More recently, she has noticed her abdomen becoming distended. Her symptoms have progressed to the stage where she is now experiencing shortness of breath and has difficulty mobilising. She migrated from Vietnam and has lived in Australia for the past 15 years. Her medical history is unremarkable and she does not use any medications. She does not smoke, drinks about a glass of wine a day and eats a well-balanced diet. On examination, there are decreased breath sounds at the lung bases. Cardiac examination reveals no murmurs, JVP 2 cm above sternal angle. Her abdomen is moderately distended, and the liver cannot be palpated. Shifting dullness is evident. There is bilateral pedal oedema and periorbital puffiness. The rest of the physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStandard laboratory investigations are performed and she has a diagnostic paracentesis. Her serum albumin is 25 g/L (36-47), serum total protein 50 g/L (64-83), ascites proteins 23 g/L, ascites albumin 16 g/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to be diagnostic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echocardiogram","Pelvic ultrasound","Liver biopsy","Tuberculin skin test","24-hour urine protein"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation of painless abdominal, pedal, and periorbital swelling, along with shortness of breath and difficulty mobilising, could be consistent with the nephrotic syndrome. A massive proteinuria would be responsible for the hypoalbuminaemia (less than 30 g/L), with resulting hyperlipidaemia and oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has ascites in the setting of a low serum ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) (\u0026lt;11 g/L), indicating the aetiology is not portal hypertension, and low ascitic protein (\u0026lt;25 g/L) indicating low protein overall. Important causes to consider in the situation of low SAAG ascites include peritoneal metastatic disease, chronic peritoneal infection (tuberculosis) and the nephrotic syndrome. If the underlying cause of this patient\u0027s problem was malignancy or tuberculosis, she would have more systemic symptoms such as anorexia, malaise and weight loss. In their absence the most likely diagnosis is the nephrotic syndrome, making a\u003Cstrong\u003E 24-hour urine protein\u003C/strong\u003E the most appropriate diagnostic investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow protein ascites refers to the presence of ascitic fluid with a low protein content, typically less than 25 g/L and would be seen in TB, peritoneal dialysis and protein losing enteropathies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be helpful if the patient had hepatic congestion in the setting of elevated SAAG and an elevated ascitic protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E to assess for potential ovarian malignancy would be indicated if the patient had a low SAAG and an elevated ascitic protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E liver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be helpful to assess for causes of cirrhosis if the patient had an elevated SAAG and a low ascitic protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBearing in mind that this woman comes from a part of the world where tuberculosis is endemic, it would be reasonable to do a \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculin skin test\u003C/strong\u003E if the patient had an elevated ascitic protein as well as low SAAG. However, this test would not be diagnostic, and further tuberculosis testing would be necessitated. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["SAAG is generally low (\u003C1.1 g/dL) in ascites not due to portal hypertension, as in cases of infection or malignancy.","SAAG is high (\u22651.1 g/dL) in portal hypertension-related ascites, as in cases of liver cirrhosis or congestive heart failure."],"references":["Huang LL, Xia HH, Zhu SL. Ascitic Fluid Analysis in the Differential Diagnosis of Ascites: Focus on Cirrhotic Ascites. J Clin Transl Hepatol. 2014 Mar;2(1):58-64. doi: 10.14218/JCTH.2013.00010. Epub 2014 Mar 15. PMID: 26357618; PMCID: PMC4521252."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28157"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28157"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-04T08:57:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T19:58:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4999"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag